neighsyncd and intfsyncd are two different processes, there is no guarantee of processing order, also the messages go through DB interface.
It is possible that arp entry for an interface gets processed after the interface has been deleted, then orchagent will try to process this arp entry for ever.  It is unlikely to happen, could we exclude such possibility in current code flow?    

It looks all the problems are caused by the inter-dependency between portorch and bufforch.   
instead of checking  gPortsOrch->isInitDone() only,  
```
    if (!gPortsOrch->isInitDone())
    {
        return;
    }
```

both gPortsOrch->isInitDone() and gBufferOrch->isInitDone()(`TODO`) should be checked for doTask() of other orch.
```
    if (!gPortsOrch->isInitDone() || !!gBufferOrch->isInitDone())
    {
        return;
    }
```
This way, let portorch and bufforch finish their internal fight,  don't bring others down with them.

If my understanding is correct,  with the change, no initPort() will be called until PortConfigDone is received.  The code logic below will block the au, speed, fec setting from being applied before PortConfigDone.  Not sure how they will be applied later.

Also gBufferOrch->isPortReady(alias) brings more dynamics here.

```c++
            if (!gBufferOrch->isPortReady(alias))
